The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Godrej arm eyes Rs 1000cr turnover
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Godrej arm eyes Rs 1000cr turnover
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Calcutta, Sept. 24: Godrej Security Equipment Division is targeting a turnover of Rs 1,000 crore in the next four to five years.        
	The Godrej amp; Boyce division, which offers a range of security equipment and solutions, is expecting a turnover of Rs 400 crore by the end of this fiscal.         
	According to D.E. Byramjee, vice-president and business head of Godrej Security, With more companies as well as the government becoming aware of the need for comprehensive security solutions, we expect to hit the Rs 1,000-crore mark by 2012-13.         
	We are growing anywhere between 25 and 30 per cent year-on-year. Our exports should also expand proportionately, he said.        
	The domestic market for security components and solutions is estimated to be Rs 4,000 crore.         
	Though there are companies that sell individual security components such as cameras, video phones and alarms, Godrej Security is the only firm to provide an entire range of security solutions  from physical barriers to computerised sensors and software.        
	Offices and homes constitute around 20-25 per cent of the companys turnover. Integrated security solutions is set to contribute Rs 50 crore to the companys turnover this fiscal and this is expected to double in the next fiscal.        
	Most of the security components are produced in the groups integrated manufacturing facility in Mumbai, while the sophisticated electronic devices are imported.        
	We are installing a robotic paint shop at our factory and also expanding the manufacturing capacity this fiscal, Byramjee said .                                                                                                                                     
